This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Hearing on December 5, 2022 at 08:30 am.

8:47 AM; Case called for Hearing.  Defendant Christopher R Narcisse appeared by video.  Attorney Preston James Smead appeared by video for Christopher R Narcisse.  Prosecuting attorney Christian Farina in court for the State of Wisconsin. All parties have agreed that some may have the hearing conducted remotely. This hearing has met the statutory standards for video conferencing.  Atty. Smead provides an update; he was just retained and needs more time to review discovery and work on a resolution with the State.  Atty. Smead requests another further proceedings date in about 30-45 days.  No objection by the State.  Court adjourns for further proceedings.  Atty. Smead would request to appear by Zoom for the next court date.  Court will allow the defendant and counsel to appear by Zoom for the next court date, but notes that the next court date after that the court will require all parties to appear in person.
Hearing scheduled for December 5, 2022 at 08:30 am.
